{"title_page": "Ralph Goodale", "text_new": "{{Infobox CanadianMP\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable]]\n|name             = Ralph Goodale\n|honorific-suffix = {{post-nominals|country=CAN|LIB|PC|size=100%}}\n|image            = Ralph Goodale 2013.jpg\n|office           = Deputy Leader of the [[Liberal Party of Canada]]\n|leader           = [[Michael Ignatieff]]<br>[[Bob Rae]] (interim)<br>[[Justin Trudeau]]\n|term_start       = September 7, 2010\n|term_end         = November 3, 2015<ref>[https://lop.parl.ca/sites/ParlInfo/default/en_CA/People/Profile?personId=4487 Library of Parliament]</ref>\n|predecessor      = [[Michael Ignatieff]]\n|successor        = \n|office1          = [[Minister of Public Safety and Emergency Preparedness]]\n|primeminister1   = [[Justin Trudeau]]\n|term_start1      = November 4, 2015\n|term_end1        = November 19, 2019\n|predecessor1     = [[Steven Blaney]]\n|successor1       = [[Bill Blair (politician)|Bill Blair]]\n|office2          = [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Minister of Finance]]\n|primeminister2   = [[Paul Martin]]\n|term_start2      = December 11, 2003\n|term_end2        = February 6, 2006\n|predecessor2     = [[John Manley]]\n|successor2       = [[Jim Flaherty]]\n|office3          = [[Minister of Public Services and Procurement|Minister of Public Works and Government Services]]\n|primeminister3   = [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]]\n|term_start3      = May 26, 2002\n|term_end3        = December 11, 2003\n|predecessor3     = [[Don Boudria]]\n|successor3       = [[Stephen Owen (politician)|Stephen Owen]]\n|office4          = [[Minister of Natural Resources (Canada)|Minister of Natural Resources]]\n|primeminister4   = [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]]\n|term_start4      = June 11, 1997\n|term_end4        = January 14, 2002\n|predecessor4     = [[Anne McLellan]]\n|successor4       = [[Herb Dhaliwal]]\n|office5          = [[Minister of Agriculture (Canada)|Minister of Agriculture and Agri-Food]]\n|primeminister5   = [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]]\n|term_start5      = November 4, 1993\n|term_end5        = June 10, 1997\n|predecessor5     = [[Charles Mayer (politician)|Charles Mayer]]\n|successor5       = [[Lyle Vanclief]]\n|parliament6      = Canadian\n|riding6          = [[Regina\u2014Wascana]]\n|term_start6      = October 19, 2015\n|term_end6        = October 20, 2019\n|predecessor6     = ''Riding established''\n|successor6       = [[Michael Kram]]\n|term_start7      = October 25, 1993\n|term_end7        = June 2, 1997\n|predecessor7     = [[Larry Schneider (politician)|Larry Schneider]]\n|successor7       = ''Riding dissolved''\n|riding8          = [[Regina\u2014Wascana|Wascana]]\n|parliament8      = Canadian\n|term_start8      = June 2, 1997\n|term_end8        = October 18, 2015\n|predecessor8     = ''Riding established''\n|successor8       = ''Riding dissolved''\n|office9          = [[Legislative Assembly of Saskatchewan|Member of the Legislative Assembly]]<br />for [[Assiniboia-Gravelbourg]]\n|term_start9      = October 20, 1986\n|term_end9        = January 1, 1988\n|predecessor9     = [[Allen Engel]]\n|successor9       = [[John Thomas Wolfe|Jack Wolfe]]\n|riding10         = [[Assiniboia (electoral district)|Assiniboia]]\n|parliament10     = Canadian\n|term_start10     = July 8, 1974\n|term_end10       = May 22, 1979\n|predecessor10    = [[Bill Knight]]\n|successor10      = [[Leonard Gustafson]]\n|birth_name       = Ralph Edward Goodale\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1949|10|5}}\n|birth_place      = [[Regina, Saskatchewan]], Canada\n|death_date       = \n|death_place      = \n|party            = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]]\n|spouse           = Pam Goodale\n|alma_mater       = [[University of Regina]]<br />[[University of Saskatchewan College of Law|University of Saskatchewan]]\n}}\n\n'''Ralph Edward Goodale''' {{postnom|PC}} (born October 5, 1949) is a Canadian politician and former [[Minister of Public Safety and Emergency Preparedness|Minister of Public Safety]] under [[Justin Trudeau]]. He was [[Canada]]'s [[Minister of Finance (Canada)|Minister of Finance]] from 2003 to 2006, and leader of the [[Saskatchewan Liberal Party]] from 1981 to 1988. He was the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] Member of Parliament for [[Regina-Wascana]] from 1993 to 2019 (the riding was known as simply [[Wascana]] from 1997 to 2015), having previously served as the member for [[Assiniboia (electoral district)|Assiniboia]] from 1974 to 1979. He was named Opposition [[House Leader]] by interim Liberal leader [[Bill Graham (Canadian politician)|Bill Graham]] in 2006, and continued to serve in this role under the leadership of [[St\u00e9phane Dion]] and [[Michael Ignatieff]] until September 2010 when he was promoted to [[Deputy Leader]]\u2014a post he retained under Trudeau.\n\n==Early life==\nGoodale was born in [[Regina, Saskatchewan]] and raised on a farm near [[Wilcox, Saskatchewan]], the son of Winnifred Claire (Myers) and Thomas Henry Goodale.<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=yHQnAQAAMAAJ&q=Thomas+Henry+Goodale+and+Winnifred+Claire+Goodale&dq=Thomas+Henry+Goodale+and+Winnifred+Claire+Goodale&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi6-4rA67zlAhULWN8KHe7MAL8Q6AEwAXoECAkQAQ]</ref><ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=X4cOAQAAMAAJ&q=Thomas+Henry+Goodale+and+Winnifred+Claire+Goodale&dq=Thomas+Henry+Goodale+and+Winnifred+Claire+Goodale&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi6-4rA67zlAhULWN8KHe7MAL8Q6AEwAHoECAQQAQ]</ref> He was a member of [[Scouts Canada]] and earned the rank of Queen's Scout.<ref>[http://www.scouts.ca/dnn/MediaCentre/AnnualGeneralMeeting2009/tabid/1748/Default.aspx ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091128082926/http://www.scouts.ca/dnn/MediaCentre/AnnualGeneralMeeting2009/tabid/1748/Default.aspx |date=November 28, 2009 }}</ref> He first attended the [[University of Regina|University of Saskatchewan, Regina Campus]] and then obtained a law degree from the [[University of Saskatchewan]] in [[Saskatoon]], where he was awarded the Gold Medal for academic achievement.\n\n==Federal politics, 1974\u20131979==\nActive at politics from a young age, he was first elected to the [[House of Commons of Canada|Parliament of Canada]] in the [[1974 Canadian federal election|1974 election]] at the age of 24 from the seat of [[Assiniboia (electoral district)|Assiniboia]]. He served as a government backbencher until the [[1979 Canadian federal election|1979 election]], when he was defeated.\n\n==Provincial politics==\nIn 1981, Goodale was named leader of the [[Saskatchewan Liberal Party]].\n\nHe led that party to a very poor showing in the [[1982 Saskatchewan general election|1982 provincial election]], in which the party received 4.51% of the popular vote and won no seats in the [[Legislative Assembly of Saskatchewan|provincial legislature]]. However, Goodale was the only Liberal candidate to receive more than 1,000 votes.<ref>[http://www.saskarchives.com/web/seld/2-13.pdf ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928101157/http://www.saskarchives.com/web/seld/2-13.pdf |date=September 28, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe party won 9.99% of the vote in the [[1986 Saskatchewan general election|1986 provincial election]], but only Goodale was elected to the legislature. Goodale ran on a platform of fiscal responsibility in this election, arguing that both the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Saskatchewan|Progressive Conservative]] and [[Saskatchewan New Democratic Party|New Democrat]] (NDP) parties favoured excessive spending policies, typified by their proposals for a Keynesian-style stimulation of the provincial economy through subsidized home improvement and renovation schemes.\n\n==Return to federal politics==\n\n===Defeated in 1988 election===\nGoodale resigned as leader to run for the federal Liberals in the [[1988 Canadian federal election|1988 election]] for the seat of [[Regina\u2014Wascana]], but he was narrowly defeated by former Regina mayor [[Larry Schneider (politician)|Larry Schneider]], who later went on to serve briefly in [[Kim Campbell]]'s cabinet. Beginning earlier that year and prior to his resignation, Goodale's executive assistant was [[Jason Kenney]]. Kenney would become a [[Conservative Party of Canada]] MP in a [[Calgary]] riding and later Premier of Alberta.\n\nGoodale then spent five years in the private sector, working for companies such as the Pioneer Life Assurance Company, Pioneer Lifeco Inc., and Sovereign Life Insurance Co.; he has stated in interviews that he felt his political career had ended.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n===In government, 1993-2006===\n[[File:Ralph Goodale free alternative.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Goodale in 2004.]]\nGoodale contested Regina-Wascana again in the [[1993 Canadian federal election|1993 federal election]] and was elected as part of the Liberal landslide that year. As a member of the new [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien|Chr\u00e9tien]] [[Cabinet of Canada|cabinet]], Goodale was named [[Minister of Agriculture (Canada)|Minister of Agriculture and Agri-Food]]. He has the prenominal \"the Honourable\" and the postnominal \"PC\" for life by virtue of being made a member of the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada]] on November 4, 1993.<ref>[http://www.pco-bcp.gc.ca/default.asp?Language=E&Page=InformationResources&Sub=PrivyCouncilMembers Biodata] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040812141548/http://www.pco-bcp.gc.ca/default.asp?Language=E&Page=InformationResources&Sub=PrivyCouncilMembers |date=August 12, 2004 }}</ref>  He has been reelected for this riding, known as Wascana from 1997 to 2015, at every election since then.\n\nIn 1997, he became the [[Minister of Natural Resources (Canada)|Minister of Natural Resources]].  In May 2002, he was named [[Minister of Public Works and Government Services]], a few weeks after the Auditor General [[Sheila Fraser]] issued a report accusing the department of inappropriate contracting practices.<ref>Martin, Lawrence ''Iron Man'', Toronto: Viking, 2003 page 358</ref> This began the exposure of the [[Sponsorship scandal]].\n\nA close ally of [[Paul Martin]], Goodale was appointed to the senior portfolio of Finance Minister when Martin became [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] on December 12, 2003. In that capacity he tabled two consecutive balanced budgets and launched the Government's productivity agenda.\n\nOn December 28, 2005, a letter surfaced from [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) [[List of Royal Canadian Mounted Police commissioners|Commissioner]] [[Giuliano Zaccardelli]] confirming the force was launching a criminal investigation into whether details regarding government tax policies relating to income trust funds were leaked from the Finance Minister's office.  Goodale said he would co-operate completely with any investigation, but would not step aside while the RCMP continued their probe. The investigation dealt only with the Department of Finance, and not the minister himself.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/rcmp-to-investigate-allegations-of-income-trust-leak-1.543497|title=RCMP to investigate allegations of income trust leak|publisher=CBC News|date=2005-12-29 |accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref> On February 15, 2007 the RCMP announced the conclusion of the income trust investigation and laid a charge of 'Breach of Trust' against [[Serge Nadeau]], an official in the Department of Finance,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.gc.ca/cfmx/view/en/index.jsp?articleid=276859 |title=RCMP investigation conclusion |publisher=News.gc.ca |date=2011-04-20 |accessdate=2011-12-17}}</ref> who pleaded guilty in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.guelphmercury.com/news-story/2740270-former-finance-department-bureaucrat-pleads-guilty-to-illegal-stock-trades|title=Former Finance Department bureaucrat pleads guilty to illegal stock trades|date=7 May 2010|accessdate=5 March 2019|website=www.guelphmercury.com|publisher=Guelph Mercury}}</ref> Goodale was cleared of any wrongdoing,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canada.com/topics/news/national/story.html?id=98a291f4-69a5-4862-8117-6fbe609f5b2a&k=36017 |title=Goodale cleared in trust case |publisher=Canada.com |date=2007-02-16 |accessdate=2011-12-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214202935/http://www.canada.com/topics/news/national/story.html?id=98a291f4-69a5-4862-8117-6fbe609f5b2a&k=36017 |archivedate=2012-02-14 }}</ref> and blamed the NDP's [[Judy Wasylycia-Leis]] for sabotaging the Liberals in the 2006 election.<ref name=\"taber1\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/ottawa-notebook/first-went-their-colleagues-now-the-grits-are-losing-office-space/article614784/ | location=Toronto | work=The Globe and Mail | first=Jane | last=Taber | title=First went their colleagues, now the Grits are losing office space | date=May 31, 2011|accessdate=2015-11-10}}</ref>\n\n===In opposition, 2006-2015===\nGoodale was re-elected to the House of Commons in the general election on [[2006 Canadian federal election|January 23, 2006]] but lost his cabinet position with the Liberal defeat.\n\n====2006 Liberal Party leadership election====\nAfter the Liberals' defeat and Paul Martin's election night announcement that he would be resigning as party leader, Goodale initially indicated that he was not interested in succeeding Martin in that post. \"I do not anticipate ever having to cross that bridge,\" he said. \"I rule it out.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Ralph Goodale rules out run for Liberal leadership {{!}} CBC News |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ralph-goodale-rules-out-run-for-liberal-leadership-1.623610 |accessdate=December 14, 2018 |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=April 21, 2006 |language=en}}</ref> On March 13, 2006, the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' reported that Goodale was reconsidering his decision, and stated that he may enter the [[2006 Liberal Party of Canada leadership election|Liberal leadership election]] after all.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gordon |first1=Sean |title=Rae speaks today, and Liberals are listening; Ex-NDP premier not expected to formally announce leadership bid yet But Winnipeg address raises profile in a crowded field of potential rivals |publisher=[[The Toronto Star]] |date=March 13, 2006}}</ref> In the end, he declined, citing his inability to speak French as a key reason. On November 28, 2006, he endorsed [[Bob Rae]] to be the next leader of the Liberal Party.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Whittington |first1=Les |title=Goodale backing boosts Rae bid |url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/toronto-star/20061129/281663955515563 |accessdate=December 14, 2018 |publisher=[[The Toronto Star]] |date=November 29, 2006}}</ref> After the third ballot, Bob Rae, who finished third, was eliminated. Goodale then endorsed [[St\u00e9phane Dion]], the eventual winner.\n\nGoodale was opposed to [[David Orchard]]'s candidacy in the by-election for [[Desneth\u00e9\u2014Missinippi\u2014Churchill River]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Delacourt |first1=Susan |title=Dion accused of snubbing Orchard |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/2008/01/05/dion_accused_of_snubbing_orchard.html |accessdate=December 14, 2018 |publisher=[[The Toronto Star]] |date=January 5, 2008 |language=en}}</ref> Dion terminated the nomination contest and appointed [[Joan Beatty]] as the candidate.\n\n====Proposed coalition government, 2008====\nGoodale was re-elected once more in the [[2008 Canadian federal election|fall of 2008]]. One month later, in November 2008, the three [[Opposition (politics)|opposition parties]] in the [[40th Canadian Parliament|Canadian parliament]] indicated their intention to defeat the [[Stephen Harper]] government in a [[motion of no confidence]], and expressed their desire for [[Governor General of Canada|Governor General]] [[Micha\u00eblle Jean]] to ask a member of the opposition to form a new government. While there was initially some speculation that Goodale would become Prime Minister of Canada as leader of the proposed [[coalition government]],<ref>{{cite news| first=Les| last=Whittington|author2=Tonda MacCharles |author3=Bruce Campion-Smith | title=Tories blink first in showdown| work=[[Toronto Star]]| date=November 30, 2008| accessdate=December 14, 2018|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2008/11/30/tories_blink_first_in_showdown.html| quote=One prominent name being mentioned is former Liberal finance minister Ralph Goodale.}}</ref> the coalition agreement simply made \"the leader of the Liberal Party\" Prime Minister. The Liberals agreed shortly after that [[St\u00e9phane Dion]] would lead the government on an interim basis until a new Liberal leader was chosen.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/liberals-ndp-bloc-sign-deal-on-proposed-coalition-1.700119|title=Liberals, NDP, Bloc sign deal on proposed coalition|work=[[CBC News]]|date=December 1, 2008|accessdate=December 14, 2018}}</ref> In the end, parliament was [[2008\u201309 Canadian parliamentary dispute|prorogued]] by Jean at the request of the prime minister before a confidence vote could be put to the house. By the time parliament resumed in January 2009, [[Michael Ignatieff]] had become interim leader of the party. He did not seek to bring down the government and agreed to support Harper's budget with amendments.\n\n====2011 election====\nGoodale was one of the 34 Liberal MPs who was returned in the [[2011 Canadian federal election|2011 federal election]], the worst showing by the Liberal Party of Canada in history.\n\nThe NDP surpassed the Liberals in number of seats, becoming the official opposition, resulted in  priority in choosing parliamentary offices. They requested that Goodale forfeit his suite in the coveted Central Block. The Liberals saw this as a measure of disrespect to Goodale, noting that he had seniority as a former cabinet minister and house leader, despite this being standard practice and noting  the Conservatives had not asked any Liberals to give up their offices.<ref name=\"taber1\"/>\n\n===In government, 2015-2019===\nThe Liberals won a majority government in the [[2015 Canadian federal election|2015 federal election]], and Goodale was re-elected to a ninth term in the House of Commons, once again representing [[Regina\u2014Wascana]] as a consequence of redistricting.  He was named [[Minister of Public Safety and Emergency Preparedness]] by Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/goodale-sworn-in-minister-of-public-safety-1.3303596|title=Saskatchewan MP Ralph Goodale sworn in as minister of public safety|work=[[CBC News]]|date=November 4, 2015|accessdate=November 5, 2015}}</ref> He is the only MP to serve in government with both Pierre and Justin Trudeau.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/ralph-goodale-only-mp-to-serve-under-both-trudeau-prime-ministers-1.3283150 |title=Ralph Goodale only MP to serve under both Trudeau prime ministers |last=Cassidy |first=Tiffany |date=October 21, 2015 |work=[[CBC News]] |access-date=November 5, 2015}}</ref>  Mr Goodale has announced that he will seek re election in the 2019 federal election. \n\nAn [[order in council]] on November 4, 2015,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pco-bcp.gc.ca/oic-ddc.asp?viewattach=31592|title=Orders in Council - Search|last=Office|first=Government of Canada Privy Council|website=www.pco-bcp.gc.ca|language=en|access-date=2016-03-25}}</ref> places Goodale as first in line to assume the prime minister's powers & duties as ''acting prime minister'', should Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] become incapacitated. Trudeau did not appoint a deputy prime minister.\n\nDespite having represented the riding since 1993, Goodale was defeated in the 2019 federal election by more than 16 percentage points.\n\n==Post politics==\nOn March 31, 2020, Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] announced the appointment of Goodale as Special Advisor to the Government of Canada's response to [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]] crash.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6755532/ralph-goodale-special-advisor-plane-crash/| title=Ralph Goodale named special advisor to feds on Iran plane crash| date=March 31, 2020| website=globalnews.ca| url-status=live| archive-date=March 31, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331140752/https://globalnews.ca/news/6755532/ralph-goodale-special-advisor-plane-crash/}}</ref> Goodale will \"examine lessons learned\" from Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752, [[Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302]], [[Air India Flight 182]] and other air disasters and \"develop a framework to guide Canada's responses to international air disasters.\"<ref>{{cite press release| url=https://pm.gc.ca/en/news/news-releases/2020/03/31/prime-minister-announces-special-advisor-canadas-ongoing-response| title=The Prime Minister announces Special Advisor for Canada's ongoing response to the Ukraine International Airlines tragedy| date=March 31, 2020| url-status=live| archive-date=March 31, 2020| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200331140658/https://pm.gc.ca/en/news/news-releases/2020/03/31/prime-minister-announces-special-advisor-canadas-ongoing-response|publisher=[[Office of the Prime Minister (Canada)|PMO]]}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral record==\n\n=== Regina\u2014Wascana ===\n{{Canadian election result/top|CA|2019|percent=yes|change=yes|expenditures=yes}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Conservative|[[Michael Kram]]|22,186|49.56|+19.29|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Liberal|Ralph Goodale|14,998|33.50|-21.63|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|NDP|Hailey Clark|5,722|12.78|+0.23|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Green|Tamela Friesen|1,290|2.88|+0.82|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|PPC|Mario Milanovski|443|0.99|-|}}\n{{CANelec|CA|Independent |Evangeline Godron |128|0.29|-|}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total valid votes/Expense limit||100.0 &nbsp;|| }}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Total rejected ballots|||}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Turnout|44,767||}}\n{{Canadian election result/total|Eligible voters|}}\n{{CANelec/gain|CA|Conservative |Liberal|+20.46}}{{CANelec/source|Source: [[Electi